Reason: To predict the melting point of 2-methyl-1-decene, we consider the effects of its molecular structure on intermolecular interactions. Starting with decane as the basic unit, which has a melting point of around -30°C, we analyze the effects of the functional groups present. A methyl group attached to an alkene typically has a very minor effect on melting point due to a slight increase in molecular weight and weak branching, which might be around +1°C. The presence of a double bond in 1-decene theoretically could cause a small decrease in the melting point because of less efficient packing and reduced van der Waals forces, estimated as around -5°C. However, the position of the double bond at the terminal end allows for more linear packing than if it were internal, thus minimizing this effect.
